I am sure that most engineering students realize that
when they leave the University they are classified as an
alumnus and automatically become a member of the
Engineering and Mines Alumni Association. But I wonder
how many really know what their Alumni Association is
and what it does.

The Engineering and Mines Alumni Association of
the University had its start long before World War II;
but it has been since then that it has become the strong

By Charles Hosick

Organization that it is today. The Association is made up

of all Engineering and Mines Alumni throughout the
country and is headed by the E & M Alumni Council
that meets in Pittsburgh to direct the activities of the
Association. The Council is made up of E & M Alumni
and Faculty and an E & M Student. With this type of
makeup, the Council provides very close coordination
between the students, faculty and alumni.

For graduating seniors, the faculty has initiated a
Senior Social where seniors are told of the activities of
the Association and will, beginning this year, be given an
identification card which will identfy them as alumni of
the University. The association has established the G.
Raymond Fitterer Scholarship which is given each year
to a deserving student from the schools of Engineering
and Minees. This award will be presented at the Associ-
ation’s annual dinner meeting. Students are also invited
to this meeting which is the highlight of the Associations
activities.

This year the dinner meeting will be held on l\/Iarch
17 during Pitt’s Engineers Week. It will be held in the
dining room of the University Club. The program for
this meeting promises to be one of the best in the history
of the Association. The main speaker will be Dr. William
O. Baker, Vice-President —- Research of Bell Telephone
Laboratories.

Dr. Baker’s area at Bell Labs covers the physical
sciences division of physics, chemistry, chemical physics,
metallurgy and solid state electronics; the communications
principles division of mathematics, visual and acustics,
electronics and radio, and communications social science
research, and the communications systems division of
guided wave research, communications technique research
and systems research.

Dr. Baker received his B.S. in 1935 from Washington
College in Maryland. He then entered graduate study at
Princeton and received his Ph. D. in 1938. His doctoral
work at Princeton was mainly in the area which is today
called solid state research. His work dealt mainly with
determining electrical properties of molecular crystals.
From there Dr. Baker began research in physical chemis-
try at Bell Labs in 1939. He has concentrated much of his
efforts on the Study of Macromolecules, the basic elements
of plastics, fibers, natural and synthetic rubbers, and
tissues of growing plants and animals. These substances
are of particular interest to Bell Labs, as the chief
electrical insulators in communications systems.

DR. WILLIAM O. BAKER

In the early 1940’s Dr. Baker was responsible for
Bell Labs part in the program of polymer research set up.
under the rubber director’s office. This research led to
the discovery of a new kind of synthetic polymer mole-
cular called “microgel”.

He has spent 15 years of active research in the area
of polymers and has contributed some 40 research papers
to the field. In addition, Dr. Baker holds about 14
patents in subjects involving high polymers, including a
recent one on a method of increasing the strength of solid
fuels used in rocket propellents.

Since 1954, his work has been mainly administrative,
serving first as, director of research -4 physical sciences
and currently as vice—president — research. Dr. Baker
has indeed a very long and distinguished record both
academically and professionally and I am sure that his
talk will be both extremely interesting and timely.

With this dinner, the Association is initiating a
Distinguished Alumni Award, whch will be given to two
very distinguished gentlemen and alumni of the schools
of Engineering and Mines.

One will be awarded to Mr. Marcus A. Follansbee.
Mr. Follansbee was graduated from the school of Mines
in 1914 with an E. M. degree. As an undergraduate, Mr.
Follansbee was quite active in University activities. He
was a member of Delta Tau Delta Fraternity, Student
Council and the Athletic Committee. He was also Business
Manager of the OWL, Assistant Manager of the football
team and president of his senior class.

After his graduation from Pitt, he began his career
with Follansbee Steel Corp. and rose to the presidency in
1948.

Mr. Follansbee took a very active part in community
affairs and has served as trustee of several organizations.
Mr. Follansbee has contributed very generously to the
University and is indeed worthy of a Distinguished
Alumni Award.

The other awardee is Mr. George M. Bevier. Mr.
Bevier was also graduated from the school of Mines. He
received a B.S. degree from the school in 1913.

