The tiny atom, like the lumbering dinosaur, has left permanent “fossil” tracks in the earth’s
rocks. Overlooked by scientists until now, the newly-discovered atomic tracks found by G. E.
scientists hold a key to the age of the minerals in which they are preserved.

The atomic tracks were discovered in a piece of mica, a mineral found in rocks throughout
the world. Minerals, including mica. contain. a trace of uranium, a radioactive element. The atoms
of uranium are unstable and decay at a known rate into atoms of elements that are not radio-
active. Ever since the minerals solidiﬁed from molten material, this clock has been. ticking away.
Some of the uranium atoms decay by undergoing ﬁssion fragments move away. and they leave a
trail. This damaged region, about 0.0005 inch long by a few atoms in diameter, constitutes a
permanent “fossil" record of each tick of the atomic clock.

At first the tracks could only ‘be seen with an electron microscope. However, it was dis-
covered that by dripping the sample in hydrofluoric (acid the tracks could be enlarged enough to
be seen even through a low—power optical microscope.

After the mica was etched, the tracks were counted. The next task was to determine the total
amount of uranium in the sample. This was done by irradiating the sample in a nuclear reactor,
splitting artiﬁcally some of the remaining atoms. After the sample was again etched. a new count
was made. The age of the mica was determined by calculating the ratio of the old tracks to the new.

The new dating technique, which can be performed quickly and inexpensively by the geology
department of any college, is not limited to terrestrial rocks. It also can be used to sudy the history
of meteorites, chunks of interplanetary debris that sometimes plunge to the earth after a ﬁery ﬂight

through space. The results may give new clues to the age and origin of the solar system.

Rubber that pours is a new development from the research labs
of General Electric. The new material is called RTV (room temperature
vulcanizing) liquid silicone rubber and will be used for low volume
requirements for duplication of small metal objects ranging from pattern
letters to jewelry through rubber molds.

The rubber is a high temperature resistant material capable of with-
standing temperatures of 600° F and above. The mold is obtained by
pouring the rubber upon the object and allowing the rubber to c11re for
24 hours at room temperature or within three hours at 150° F.

In studies conducted by General Electric, up to 35 reproductions
have been made from a single mold without apparent damage to the
rubber. No parting agent is required to separate a cast part from the
silicone mold as silicone rubber releases easily from other objects.

Mold life has been found to be improved by an over-night bake
at 200° F to 300° F and is still further increased by aging the mold
for a week or two. Although it is unlikely that satisfactory results could
be achieved with steel and some of the other metals with extremely
high melting points. it is possible to cast parts of zinc and other higher
melting metals by employing special techniques which cool the mold
while the metal is being poured. One of these that has some success
involves cooling the mold with water.

The silicone rubber molds are less costly to make than metal molds,
provide greater accuracy of detail than sand. and have a much greater
life expectancy than wood.

